                                                <p style="font-weight: bold;">
                                                    There are 3 main ways in which you can establish the initial valuation for a business. These are:
                                                </p>
                                                <ul>
                                                    <li>Multiple of profits</li>
                                                    <li>Asset Value</li>
                                                    <li>Discounted Cash Flow (DCF)</li>
                                                </ul>
                                                <br />

                                                <h3>Multiple of Profits</h3>

                                                <p>The multiple of profits method involves adjusting the profits of the business to add back any benefits the current owner receive. These include things like running personal vehicles through the business to pension contributions. You can also re-add any one-off expenses that wouldn't recur for the new owner.</p>

                                                <p>To calculate this, we workout the EBITDA and then add the elements above. This then gives us the adjusted profits figure.</p>

                                                <h3>Asset Value</h3>

                                                <p>When a business is not massively profitable but has a lot of assets, we look at the asset value. Depending on how the business is set-up, we may use different methods. For a Limited Company you'd use the balance sheet to calculate the net current position. This would then represent the asset value.</p>

                                                <p>In a sole trader set up, the assets and liabilities are a little different. They are the individuals, so taking account of the liabilities is not usually necessary. You would simple need to take the actual asset value.</p>

                                                <h4>What is a business asset?</h4>

                                                <p>A business asset is something that the business owns and delivers value to the business. Assets can be used for services, to produce goods and fund operations. An asset could be a machine, building, stock, furniture or intellectual property. They are essential anything that is owned by the business intended for business use.</p>

                                                <h3>Discounted Cash Flow (DCF)</h3>

                                                <p>The DCF method is generally used to value larger businesses, is usually a more accurate way to value a business.  The method uses the businesses future cash flows discounted to today’s money.</p>

                                                <p>If all this information is a little overwhelming, don't worry, we are here to help. Youy can either visit our guides or get in touch with our team. We're always available to help you with your valuation.</p>


