                                                <h4>Why do I need to value my business?</h4>

                                                <p>Valuing your business is more than just getting a price for a sale.  A valuation establishes a base value which helps to inform financial goals and business strategies. A business valuation also allows you to understand your businesses potential for growth.</p>

                                                <p>Also, if your looking to sell your business, a valuation is extremely important. It helps to determine the fair market price for your business.</p>

                                                <p>If a business is over-priced , it will not attract any buyer interest and is unlikely to sell at all. If a sale price too low, you may be cheating yourself out of a large sum of money. By correctly valuing your business, your ensuring all parties get the correct deal in a business sale.</p>

                                                <hr />

                                                <!-- What tax will I pay when selling my business? -->
                                                <h4>What tax will I pay when selling my business?</h4>

                                                <p>When selling a business, the  sale of shares is subject to Capital Gains Tax (CGT) . The amount paid in CGT will be influenced by your personal tax circumstances.</p>

                                                <p>Whilst the conditions for Entrepreneurs' Relief (a CGT rate of 10 per cent) may appear simple, we recommend you take formal advice where the transaction structure is unusually complex, notwithstanding our panel of lawyers are normally happy to give a basic level of CGT advice.</p>

                                                <hr />

                                                <!-- How long does it take to sell a business? -->
                                                <h4>How long does it take to sell a business?</h4>

                                                <p>Unfortunately there is no single answer as to how long it will take to sell a business. The sale of business is generally dependent on the demand for the business that is being sold. Generally businesses with a smaller value will sell quicker as they have a larger pool of potential buyers. Businesses selling for a larger price have a smaller pool, and will also need more due diligence.</p>

                                                <p>According to various studies, the sale of a business generally takes around 6 to 9 months. If your looking for a sale quicker than this then you need to ensure your asking price is enticing.</p>

                                                <hr />

                                                <!-- What will buyers look for in my business? -->
                                                <h4>What will buyers look for in my business?</h4>

                                                <p>When someone's looking to buy a business, they are generally looking for a business that has the potential for growth. The buyer will want to lower their risk to maximise their investment. This means that they'll do a lot of due diligence into various attributes in the business.</p>

                                                <p>Purchases will want to access your financial conditions. This will include your financial statements, tax returns, depreciation schedules and payroll records. They will also want to see your earnings (profit before tax) for up to the past five years, if they are available.</p>

                                                <p>They'll also want to review the assets of your business. This will be to ensure that they not only exist, but they are in quality order. This could include facilities, equipment/vehicles, inventories and leasehold improvements.</p>

                                                <p>It's important that you have a professional who can help you during the sale of your business. This will drastically improve the chance  of surviving due diligence, closing the transaction, and getting the most value the market will support.</p>
